            <pb n="7" facs="#f0001"/>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="#k">Von Humboldt.</hi>&#x2014;The <hi rendition="#i">Prussian
                    Universal Gazette</hi> publishes the<lb break="yes"/>following
                letter:&#x2014;&#x201C;Whenever I find my name quoted in an un-<lb break="no"
                />favourable manner, in a political or literary point of view, in the jour-<lb
                    break="no"/>nals, I make it a point to remain silent; but I break through that
                    rule<lb break="yes"/>when any calumny is directed against one of my intimate
                friends. The<lb break="yes"/>
                <hi rendition="#i">Manheim Gazette</hi> of the 28th ult. annonnces the following,
                under the<lb break="yes"/>head Berlin:&#x2014;&#x2018;We have been informed that M.
                Arago has declined to<lb break="yes"/>accept the Prussian Order of Merit, and has
                sent it back. This report<lb break="yes"/>has been confirmed, and M. Arago has
                written on the subject to Alex-<lb break="no"/>andre Von Humboldt.&#x2019; This
                statement is as ridiculous as it is absurd.<lb break="yes"/>The King of Prussia,
                after conferring the Order of Merit on a number<lb break="yes"/>of persons
                unconnected with the army, simultaneously appointed<lb break="yes"/>knights of that
                order M. Arago, M. Letronne, M. de Chateaubriand,<lb break="yes"/>M. Daguerre, M.
                Ingres, M. Horace Vernet, and M. Gay Lussac. M.<lb break="yes"/>Arago was the first
                who replied, on the 8th of June, 1842, that he ac-<lb break="no"/>cepted the
                decoration. He wrote to me to that effect, in my capacity<lb break="yes"/>of
                Chancellor of the new institution, and expressed himself in terms<lb break="yes"
                />which bespoke his satisfaction.</p>
            <closer>
                <salute>&#x2014;<hi rendition="#k">Alexandre Von Humboldt.</hi>&#x2014;</salute>
            </closer>
            <lb break="yes"/>
            <dateline>Berlin, Nov. 1, 1843.&#x201D;</dateline>
            <lb break="yes"/>
        </body>
        <back/>
